vels, including phonology, morphology and syntax in noun phrases and the verb complex, and syntax at the clause- and sentence-level. Throughout the grammar, the described phenomena are related to the current research on typological and Oceanic linguistics. Typologically unusual features of Papapana include multiple reduplication, inverse-number marking in the noun phrase and postverbal subject-indexing. The book also describes the sociolinguistic and historical context within which Papapana is spoken and highlights linguistic changes resulting from language contact. The monograph fills an important gap in terms of grammatical descriptions of Bougainville Oceanic languages, and makes a significant contribution to the field of Oceanic linguistics, and to future comparative linguistic and typological research.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 4aAustronesische Sprachen. 4aPapuaneuguinea. 4aSprachtypologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAustronesian.  aOceanic Languages.  aPapua New Guinea.  aTypology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Frontlist 2020z97831107431660 cEPUBz97815015098960 cprintz978150151680140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150150997140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501509971423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501509971/original  a978-3-11-069627-1  DG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1b2020  a978-3-11-069628-8  DG Ebook Package English 2020b2020  a978-3-11-074316-6  De Gruyter Mouton Frontlist 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL